In an effort to improve SAC, [~aatkins] modified JIRA to detect and block email messages that are coming from a mail loop.

He wrote:

{panel}Here's the code that matters, which needs to appear early on in the handleMessage method of the AbstractMessageHandler class in JIRA:

{code}if (MailHelper.isJiraNotification(message)) {

log.warn("Message '" + message.getSubject() + "' appears to be from another instance and will be forwarded.");

return false;

}{code}

That method just takes a message and lets you know if it's a JIRA notification:
{code}public static boolean isJiraNotification(Message message) throws MessagingException {

if (message == null) return false;


String[] fingerPrintHeaders = message.getHeader("X-JIRA-FingerPrint");

if (fingerPrintHeaders != null && fingerPrintHeaders.length > 0) {

return true;

}


return false;

}
{code}{panel}

If this were to be added to JIRA core, this would benefit a large number of customers. It would need to be extended to be configurable, and to log the caught messages somewhere inside of the Admin UI (if possible). Errors in the logs should remain consistent with the style mentioned here: https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRAKB/Logs+Contain+'Received+Message+Carrying+this+JIRA+Instance+Fingerprint'+Due+to+Mail+Loop+Detected This would help admins find and identify the offending notification schemes.

